nThe missons suffers from a major problem, in that it has realtime sneak/explore/loot mode and a turn-based fighting mode, and transitions are handled very poorly. The instigator of combat gets initiative, which makes it a huge tactical advantage to be able to control position, timing and agro as combat starts. Unfortunately, the transition to and from turn-base isn't handled well, so most of the challenge is learning to navigate the transitions. \n\nAn example I struggled with many times at first: you'll be sneaking up behind a zombie, then you trigger turn based combat and move your first character a a little closer... but you didn't get close enough for him to see you. There's no agroed zombies, so combat automatically ends. The game returns to realtime and immediately the team regroups with the first member, alerting the zombie to their presence as they do so. Now combat restarts with your whole team in different positions, and since the zombie \"started combat\" he gets initiative like you're being ambushed. Now he turns and takes a big bite out of that first survivor, possibly infecting him, and now you may have to spend the rest of the game (maybe 40 hours?) making sure he's got a steady supply of medicine so he doesn't turn. \n\nA different kind of frustrating... the combat is slow. On a big map, you might sneak up and attack one zombie, but the combat system has to process the 50 other zombies all over the map (who are just standing around cuz they're across the map and haven't agroed yet). It's like we're playing a 1998 strategy game... the PC's turns tend to be five times as long as yours when nothing is happening. And if there are enemy survivors are fighting zombies somewhere across the map... then you have to wait for all the animations even though you can't see them. Tactically it's a win, but it takes soooooo long. \n\nCamera angles are bad too. You can spin the camera but not adjust the angle, and walls are high and ceilings don't always disappear when you want them to. I had one battle where we fought under a gas-station canopy where the canopy wouldn't disappear, so I just had to keep spinning the cameara, trying to get a glimpse of what was happening underneath. Thin halls and cramped rooms are difficult as well. \n\nLast gripe: Late in the game, zombies become trival enemies, but their bites can infect survivors, which is an incurable catastrophy. But if you've gotten to this point, you know how to be careful. It's not hard, it's just slow and tedious. Going through a suburb, stealth killing one zombie at a time for routine scavenging operations is mind-numbingly boring, but such a big part of the game. \n\nAnyway, all that said, pretty much everything I haven't complained about is very good. Challenging combat is fun. You need to pick your battles, as different groups have different tiers of equipment. I'll never forget the first time my squad bumped into a pair of Coyote gangsters. It's still terrifying bumping into military defectors squads with my zombie-equipped scavanging team. Monitoring your food and medicine levels is always a little tense, and it's a rush of relief when you find that rare stash of supplies. You love dumpsters, hoping for rotten fruit and scrap wood. Finding a AK47 is not nearly as satisfying as a 10lbs bag of beans (Or that time I found the twinky factory and carried back 120lbs of twinkies and raw sugar. Not sure if they'd worship me or crucify me).\n\nI'm much more patient than most gamers, but this one was too much for me. If you want to finish this game, it will take an extremely patient person (or at least someone who is committed to finishing it, regardless of whether they enjoy it). On the other hand, some people probably play the start, but set it down when it becomes a sea of routine scavanging. If you think you're one of those two types of people, maybe this game is for you, but it was just too slow for me.", "timestamp_updated": 1506591050, "written_during_early_access